# 3. まさかの遭遇

Akito: Phew... That shrine was totally packed.
Toya: Yes. I suppose that was to be expected, since it's such a famous shrine.
Toya: But I'm glad that we were both able to draw great blessings. It's an excellent way to start off the new year.
Akito: Yeah, true. We're gonna need all the luck we can get.
Akito: Still, this place is also packed with people... There might be a huge line to get into that cafe.
Toya: We may want to head there early, since you mentioned that they'd be serving only a few plates of those New Year's pancakes...
Toya: We should probably head to the cafe before visiting the sporting goods store at the mall.
Akito: You sound weirdly excited about this for some reason.
Akito: But you're right about not wasting time waiting in line. Let's head over there now.
Toya: Oh, I've been meaning to ask...
Akito: Hm?
Toya: Could you tell me more about these New Year's pancakes? I've been having a hard time figuring out how they managed to tie a Western dish to this holiday...
Akito: Oh, they gave it a Japanese twist by making it look like kagami mochi.
Akito: Apparently, it's a stack of three pancakes coated in white chocolate and a mandarin on top.
Toya: White chocolate...?! That's quite bold of them...
Akito: It is pretty strange, but a lot of people who had it last year gave good reviews.
Akito: Oh, there. It's that cafe...
Akito: Yikes, there's a huge line...
Toya: I had a feeling, but this place must be just that popular.
Toya: That being said, I don't mind waiting. We're not doing anything else other than visiting that sporting goods store, so let's get in line.
Akito: I feel kinda bad, but I agree. Let's find the end of this line...
???: Huh? Akito?
Akito: Huh?
Akito: Wait, what are you doing here?
Ena: That's my line. What are you doing here?
Airi: Alright, Ena, call off your dogs. It's New Year's, remember?
Airi: Happy New Year, Akito, Toya! I'm surprised to see you two here! Grabbing a bite?
Toya: Happy New Year, Momoi. One of their menu items caught our attention, so we came to try it.
Ena: One of their menu items...? Are you two here to try their New Year's pancakes?
Akito: Wait, don't tell me you're also here for them.
Ena: That's right... More importantly, what's with the attitude? You got here after us.
Akito: When we got here doesn't matter.
Airi: Again, you two! Quit bickering!
Airi: Look, us running into each other like this can't just be a coincidence, so let's all wait together, shall we?
Airi: So, I asked Ena this a second ago, but how do you two plan on spending New Year's?
Akito: New Year's? Well, we're going to practice singing like usual...
Toya: With the exception of tomorrow. We're actually going to play competitive Hanetsuki with some friends.
Ena: Competitive Hanetsuki?
Toya: Yes, it's Hanetsuki with rules that mirror similar sports. As you can probably see from this image, they use larger paddles and shuttlecocks.
Airi: Cool...! That's really cute, and this looks really fun!
Airi: Wait a second... We could play this during our stream...
Akito: Your stream?
Airi: Yeah! We're planning on playing a few New Year's games during our stream tomorrow...
Airi: But we had trouble coming up with ones that would be entertaining on a stream. Ena and I are actually gonna head over to the mall to see if they have anything good.
Akito: Then, why don't we all go together? We were also planning to head over to the mall after checking out this cafe.
Airi: Really? If you two are okay with it, then I'd love to have you guys there with us.
Airi: Does that sound okay, Ena?
Ena: I'm not in love with the idea of going with Akito, but I guess it would make sense for us to go together.
Akito: Hey, I heard that.
Airi: Hehe. Thanks, Ena. I really appreciate it.
Airi: And I really need to thank you two! You guys are lifesavers!
Airi: I tried searching for New Year's games we could play during our stream, but I ended up with way too many choices. It was hard to pick just one.
Akito: Yeah, I know what you mean. You can fly kites, play Kendama...
Airi: My sisters and I used to play Karuta a lot when we were little. I also remember crying a lot since I could never beat my big sis.
Ena: New Year's, huh...? We usually played that one board game about life.
Akito: Yeah... I remember a certain someone always placing a big bet that invariably put them deep in debt.
Ena: Wait, are you talking about me?
Ena: I mean, you never did anything interesting. You always ended up leading a boring life with no detours.
Akito: Stable is the word I'd use. Which is better than being underwater in my opinion.
Toya: I see. Playing games with your family certainly sounds quite fun.
Toya: My family never really did any of those things, so this is all a bit new to me.
Airi: Oh, really? Was everyone usually busy?
Toya: Yes, my dad usually performed in New Year's concerts overseas. We'd go as a family to watch him play.
Airi: Concerts?
Ena: Your family really is all about music, huh?
Waiter: Thank you for your patience. I can show you three to your table now.
Akito: Oh, we've been talking for so long that we're pretty close to the front now.
Airi: Hehe. Time sure does fly when you're having an enjoyable conversation.
Waiter: Are you our next group? I'm terribly sorry, but do you have a moment...?
Ena: Are you referring to us?
Waiter: Yes, I regret to inform you all that...
